aas:election_record.label: Maryland 1789 Electoral College, Eastern Shore

aas:elector.name: William Tilghman
aas:elector.aas:note: John Rogers was on both tickets.

aas:elector.name: William Richardson
aas:elector.aas:note: George Plater was on both tickets.

aas:overview.aas:note: Anti-Federalist electors ran full slates in both Maryland, Pennsylvania and also in some of the Virginia districts. While not organized on a national level, they were very strong in certain states. I have not been able to find out exactly for whom the electors voted for, except that they all voted for George Washington. I am not sure if that information even exists. Each elector had two votes and they all cast at least one of their votes for George Washington. How they cast their second votes is something that has yet to be known.
There was three electors for the Eastern Shore. William Tilghman, William Matthews and William Richardson were elected.
According to Preseidential Elections in Maryland, William Tilghman received 5737 votes and William Matthews received 5442 votes.

aas:sub_unit.name: Talbot
aas:sub_unit.aas:note: William Tilghman received 254 votes. Presidential Elections in Maryland. John T. Willis. Lomond Publications. 1984. Pg. 155.

aas:sub_unit.name: Annapolis
aas:sub_unit.aas:note: Votes reported in Presidential Elections in Maryland for the City of Annaplois included the County of Anne Arundel.
William Tilghman received 18 votes for Annaplois and Anne Arundel. Presidential Elections in Maryland. John T. Willis. Lomond Publications. 1984. Pg. 154.

aas:sub_unit.name: Worcester
aas:sub_unit.aas:note: William Matthews received 153 votes. Presidential Elections in Maryland. John T. Willis. Lomond Publications. 1984. Pg. 155.

aas:sub_unit.name: Montgomery
aas:sub_unit.aas:note: William Tilghman received 320 votes. Presidential Elections in Maryland. John T. Willis. Lomond Publications. 1984. Pg. 155.
